<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Match Wine Tannin Structure to Turkey Preparation</strong> - The cooking method dramatically affects wine pairing. Roasted turkey with crispy skin can handle medium-tannin reds like Côtes du Rhône or Oregon Pinot Noir, while herb-brined turkey pairs better with high-acid whites like Sancerre or Finger Lakes Riesling. The Maillard reaction from roasting creates savory compounds that complement earthy, spice-driven wines.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve Thanksgiving Wines Slightly Warmer Than Usual</strong> - With rich, warm dishes dominating the table, serve white wines at 45-50°F (rather than the standard 40-45°F) and reds at 60-65°F. This temperature adjustment helps wines maintain their fruit character against the richness of gravy, stuffing, and butter-laden sides without being overwhelmed.</li>

  <li><strong>Choose High-Acid Wines to Cut Through Rich Thanksgiving Fats</strong> - Thanksgiving dishes are loaded with butter, cream, and rendered turkey fat. Wines with bright acidity like Champagne, Chablis, or Barbera d'Alba act as palate cleansers. The acidity literally cuts through fat molecules, preventing palate fatigue and enhancing both the food and wine experience throughout the long meal.</li>

  <li><strong>Decant Young Tannic Reds 2-3 Hours Before Serving</strong> - If serving Cabernet Sauvignon, Barolo, or other structured reds with your Thanksgiving feast, decant them well in advance. The extended decanting softens tannins that might clash with the meal's sweetness (cranberry sauce, sweet potatoes) while allowing the wine's fruit to shine alongside savory turkey and herbs.</li>

  <li><strong>Use Burgundy Glasses for Both Reds and Whites</strong> - The wide bowl of Burgundy glasses concentrates the complex aromas essential for Thanksgiving wine pairing. Whether you're serving Chardonnay or Pinot Noir, these glasses capture the subtle herb, spice, and fruit notes that complement the layered flavors of traditional Thanksgiving dishes better than standard wine glasses.</li>

  <li><strong>Plan Wine Service Around the Cranberry Sauce Challenge</strong> - Cranberry sauce's tartness can make wines taste flat and overly sweet. Combat this by choosing wines with matching acidity (Sancerre, Grüner Veltliner) or off-dry wines like Gewürztraminer that complement rather than fight the cranberries' natural acidity and slight sweetness.</li>

  <li><strong>Open Aged Wines 30 Minutes Before the First Course</strong> - Mature wines (10+ years) need gentle handling for Thanksgiving service. Open them just before guests arrive to preserve delicate tertiary aromas that pair beautifully with sage stuffing and roasted vegetables. Older wines' developed earthy, mushroom, and dried fruit notes create magical pairings with traditional Thanksgiving flavors.</li>

  <li><strong>Create a Progressive Wine Experience Through the Meal</strong> - Start with sparkling wine during appetizers, move to crisp whites or light reds with the main course, then finish with a dessert wine or Port with pie. This progression prevents palate fatigue and ensures each wine enhances its specific course rather than competing with the previous selection's lingering flavors.</li>
</ol>



