    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do I choose wines that pair with multiple Thanksgiving side dishes?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Focus on wines with bright acidity and moderate tannins that can handle both sweet and savory elements—Oregon Pinot Noir, Alsatian Pinot Gris, or Beaujolais work exceptionally well. These versatile wines complement everything from cranberry sauce's tartness to stuffing's herbs and sweet potato casserole's richness. Avoid heavily oaked or high-alcohol wines that clash with the meal's complex flavor profile.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when selecting Thanksgiving wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is choosing wines that are too heavy or tannic, particularly bold Cabernet Sauvignon or heavily oaked Chardonnay, which overwhelm Thanksgiving's delicate flavors. Many hosts also forget to consider the meal's sweet elements like cranberry sauce and glazed vegetables when making selections. Instead, prioritize food-friendly wines with good acidity that enhance rather than compete with the traditional flavors.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Thanksgiving wine pairing suitable for wine beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely—Thanksgiving is actually an ideal time for wine beginners to explore pairing because the traditional menu offers predictable flavor profiles to work with. The meal's combination of savory proteins, sweet sides, and tart cranberries provides clear pairing guidelines that are easier to follow than more complex cuisines. Start with crowd-pleasing options like Pinot Noir or Riesling that showcase classic food-and-wine harmony principles.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How many bottles should I buy for Thanksgiving dinner?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Plan for about one bottle per two guests for a full Thanksgiving meal, accounting for the longer dining experience and multiple courses. Include a mix of 60% white wines (Chardonnay, Riesling, Sauvignon Blanc) and 40% light reds (Pinot Noir, Beaujolais) to accommodate diverse preferences and pairing needs. Don't forget one bottle of sparkling wine for toasts and a dessert wine if serving traditional pies.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the best non-alcoholic alternatives for Thanksgiving wine pairings?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sparkling apple cider offers the festive bubbles and fruit-forward profile that mimics Prosecco, while cranberry juice with sparkling water provides the tartness that cuts through rich foods like wine's acidity. Grape juice blends or alcohol-removed wines maintain the complexity of traditional pairings without the alcohol. These alternatives work particularly well because Thanksgiving's robust flavors don't require alcohol to create successful food pairings.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">When should I open my Thanksgiving wines before serving?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Open light, crisp whites like Sauvignon Blanc and Pinot Grigio just before serving to preserve their fresh aromatics, while richer whites like Chardonnay benefit from 15-30 minutes of air exposure. Light reds such as Pinot Noir and Beaujolais should be opened 30-60 minutes before dinner to allow gentle aeration without losing their delicate fruit character. Avoid decanting these food-friendly wines as their charm lies in their approachable, immediate drinking style.</p>
